---

## ğŸ§  Data Modeling
A star schema was implemented to ensure analytical accuracy and performance:
- **Fact Table:** Health risk observations
- **Dimension Tables:** Person, Glucose, BMI, Lifestyle, Outcome

Single-direction, many-to-one relationships were used in Power BI to maintain model integrity.

---

## ğŸ“ˆ Dashboard Features
- KPI card visuals summarizing key metrics
- Lifestyle risk analysis (calories, physical activity, family history)
- Clinical risk analysis (glucose levels, BMI)
- Risk segmentation using combined attributes
- Interactive filters and slicers
- Clear distinction between modifiable and non-modifiable risk factors

---

## ğŸ” Key Insights
- Elevated glucose levels show the strongest association with diabetes
- Higher BMI significantly increases diabetes risk
- Low physical activity amplifies lifestyle-related risk
- Family history increases susceptibility but does not determine outcome alone
- Lifestyle factors remain critical and modifiable risk contributors

---

## âš ï¸ Limitations
This analysis is observational and does not imply causation.  
The results depend on dataset assumptions and should not be interpreted as a medical diagnosis.

---

## ğŸ¯ Conclusion
The project demonstrates how data analytics and Power BI can be used to explore health risk patterns and support data-driven decision-making.  
It highlights the importance of lifestyle modification in diabetes prevention strategies.

